// Orchicon Recovery entity (docs/06_Recovery_Workflow_Engine.md,
// docs/02_Domain_Model.md §2.6, docs/07 §3.6).
//
// Recovery is a workflow, not a function. A RecoveryExecution is a
// specialized WorkerExecution whose Worker is the recovery workflow
// driver. Recovery preserves progress, minimizes context loss, and
// resumes forward motion with minimal human intervention
// (docs/06 §1). Recovery is opt-out, not opt-in: every workflow
// recovers by default (docs/06 §1).
//
// The default recovery workflow has six steps (docs/06 §3):
// capture → summarize → preserve → review → plan → resume. The engine
// picks direct checkpoint replay when a compatible adapter accepts the
// prior checkpoint; otherwise it runs the full summarize-resume path
// (docs/06 §4).
//
// Bounded auto-relax (docs/06 §11): recovery may increase a Task's budget
// by up to 25% of the original automatically (with an audit event);
// beyond 150% of the original budget, human approval is required.
//
// Task completion (docs/06 §11, docs/02 §4 #2): a Task may be marked
// succeeded by the completion Policy, by the Reviewer Worker during
// recovery, or by a human. All three paths produce an audit event with
// the actor recorded.

